<section>
  <title> Related Rates </title>
<p></p>
<exercises>
  <introduction>
    <warning>
      <p>
        If you do not draw a sketch of these problems you are
        handicapping yourself unnecessarily. <em>Draw yourself a
        picture.</em>
      </p>
    </warning>
  </introduction>
      <exercisegroup cols="2">    <title>Particle Motion</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          A particle in motion is constrained to move along the curve
          <m>y=2x^2-x</m>.
          Find the rate of change of <m>y</m> with respect to time if:
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>x=1</m> and the rate of change of <m>x</m> with respect to time is
            <m>1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p><m>3</m></p>
        </answer>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>x=12</m> and the rate of change of <m>x</m> with respect to time is
            <m>10</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p><m>470</m></p>
        </answer>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>x=15</m> and the rate of change of <m>x</m> with respect to time is
            <m>-7</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p><m>-413</m></p>
        </answer>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>x=a</m> and the rate of change of <m>x</m> with respect to time is
            <m>b</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p><m>(4a-1)b</m></p>
        </answer>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the value of <m>x</m> where the rate of change of <m>y</m> with
            respect to time is the same as the rate of change of
            <m>x</m> with respect to time.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <!-- <answer> -->
        <!--   <p><m>x=1/2</m></p> -->
        <!-- </answer> -->
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

      <exercisegroup cols="2">    <title>Cubes</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            All edges of a cube are expanding at the same rate. Find
            the rate of change of the volume of the cube when:
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Each edge has length <m>1,</m> and the rate of change of each
              edge is <m>2</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>6</m></p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Each edge has length <m>2,</m> and the rate of change of each
              edge is <m>1</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>12</m></p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Each edge has length <m>5,</m> and the rate of change of each
              edge is <m>-3</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>-225</m></p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Each edge has length <m>l,</m> and the rate of change of each
              edge is <m>r</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>3l^2r</m></p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>

      <exercisegroup cols="2">    <title>Rectangular Solids</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Find the rate of change of the surface area of a
          rectangular solid when:
        </p>
      </introduction>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Each edge has length <m>1,</m> and the rate of change of each
              edge is <m>2</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>24</m></p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Each edge has length <m>2,</m> and the rate of change of each
              edge is <m>1</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>24</m></p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Each edge has length <m>5,</m> and the rate of change of each
              edge is <m>-3</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>-180</m></p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Each edge has length <m>l,</m> and the rate of change of each
              edge is <m>r</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>12lr</m></p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>

      <exercisegroup cols="2">    <title>Expanding Circles</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            When a stone is dropped into a still lake a circular wave starts
            expanding from the point of impact.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If the radius of the wave is increasing at a rate of
              <m>1/2</m> meter per second, how fast is the area enclosed
              by the wave increasing when the radius is 2 meters?
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>2\pi</m> square meters per second</p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If the radius of the wave is increasing at a rate of <m>2</m> meters per second,
              how fast is the area enclosed by the wave increasing when the radius
              is 10 meters?
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>40\pi</m> square meters per second</p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If the radius of the wave is increasing at a rate of <m>\kappa</m> meters per second,
              how fast is the area enclosed by the wave increasing when the radius
              is <m>\rho</m> meters?
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>2\cdot\pi\cdot\rho\cdot\kappa</m> square
            meters per second</p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If the <term>circumference</term> of the wave is increasing at a rate of <m>6</m>
              meters per second, how fast is the radius increasing?
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>\frac{3}{\pi}</m> meters per second</p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If the area enclosed by the wave is increasing at a rate of <m>6</m>
              meters per second when the radius is <m>10</m>, how fast is the radius increasing?
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>\displaystyle\frac{3}{10\pi}</m> meters per second</p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If the circumference of the wave is increasing at a rate of <m>6</m>
              meters per second, find the rate of change of  the area.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p><m>\dfdx{r}{t}=6r</m></p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>

      <exercisegroup cols="2">    <title>Distance Problems</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Two  runners start running at the same time. Runner
            <m>A</m> goes  east at <m>10</m> feet per second, and
            runner <m>B</m> goes north at <m>8</m>
            feet per second.
          </p>
          <p>
            Find the rate at which the distance between them is
            changing
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              One minute (<m>60</m> seconds) later.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p> <m>120\sqrt{41}</m> feet per second</p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Two minutes  (<m>120</m> seconds) later.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p> <m>240\sqrt{41}</m> feet per second</p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Three minutes  (<m>180</m> seconds) later.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p> <m>360\sqrt{41}</m> feet per second</p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>k</m> minutes later.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              Nope. Figure this one out yourself.
            </p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
      <exercisegroup cols="2"><title>More Distance Problems</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            A runner starts running east at <m>10</m> feet per second. One
            minute later, another runner starts running north at <m>8</m>
            feet per second. Find the rate at which the distance between them is
            changing
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              One minute  after the second runner begins.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>Approximately <m>12.26</m> feet per second</p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Two minutes after the second runner begins.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>Approximately <m>12.59</m> feet per second</p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Two minutes after the <term>first</term> runner begins.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>
              Seriously? You need to look? Think about this one some
              more.
            </p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>k</m> minutes after the second runner begins.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <answer>
            <p>Nope. Figure this one out yourself.</p>
          </answer>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A silo with a diameter of <m>20</m> feet is  topped with a hemisphere. If the
        top is uniformly coated with a layer of ice <m>2</m> inches thick, and the ice is melting so
        that the thickness is decreasing at a rate of <m>1/4</m> inches per hour,
        how fast is the volume of the ice changing?
      </p>
    </statement>
        <hint>
<p>
          Be careful. The problem gives some parameters in feet and others in
          inches. 
</p>
</hint>
    <answer>
<p>
      <m>-7442\pi</m> or, approximately <m>-23,368</m> cubic inches per hour
</p>
</answer>
  </exercise>

<exercise>
<title>
Cone Problems
</title>

<introduction>
      <p>
        Sand is poured onto a horizontal surface in such a way that it
        always forms a right circular cone.
      </p>
</introduction>
<task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose that the height of the cone is always the same as
          its radius.
        </p>
        <p>
          After ten minutes the height of the cone is ten inches and
          it is increasing at <m>6</m> inches per minute. How fast is
          the volume of the cone increasing?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>600\pi</m> or approximately <m>1885</m> cubic inches per minute
        </p>
      </answer>
</task>
<task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose that the height of the cone is always the same as
          its diameter.
        </p>
        <p>
          After ten minutes the height of the cone is ten inches and
          it is increasing at <m>6</m> inches per minute. How fast is
          the volume of the cone increasing?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>100\pi</m> or approximately <m>314</m> cubic inches per minute           
        </p>
      </answer>
</task>
<task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose that the  height of the cone is always the same as
          the square of its radius. 
        </p>
        <p>
          After ten minutes the height of the cone is ten inches and
          it is increasing at <m>6</m> inches per minute. How fast is
          the volume of the cone increasing? 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\frac{200\pi}{3}</m> or approximately <m>209</m> cubic inches per minute
        </p>
      </answer>
</task>
</exercise>

